 </td><td><input type=button value="Spell Check" class=inputbutton onClick="var f=document.forms[0]; doSpell('EN', f.body, document.location.protocol + '//' + document.location.host + '/cgi?script=sproxy.cgi', true);"></td></tr></table></form><br><br><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=95%><tr><td bgcolor=#333333><table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=5 cellspacing=1><tr><td valign=top background=http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/images/bar.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top background=http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/images/bar.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 148<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/14/02 10:48:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/Cosmos/Images/northsouth_lg.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Who knows?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; Do </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->(Fusion-only &quot;clean&quot; bombs)<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  actually<br>
exist? I thought the energy needed to initiate a<br>
fusion reaction in a bomb required the power of<br>
a fission explosion?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 So far. The DOD is supposedly interested in them, because relatively clean, sub-kilotonne bombs make nuclear weapons &quot;more acceptable&quot; -meaning nobody would object too strenuously if we used them on bunkers in Iraq (or whoever is the enemy of the moment).<br>
Inertial confinement doesn't look too favorable, even in a lab, let alone a field-deployable small weapon (or an NPR ship's engine).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; If they do exist, even if only on paper, how<br>
clean... would a fusion bomb be? zero harmful<br>
radiation?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I suspect that there would be some pollution from the structure and other stuff involved in a bomb. Still, it would be far less nasty than a fission trigger.<br>
Maybe it'd be possible to use different materials, which minimizes lingering radiation. Anything we can say or expect to hear about it is speculative, because the only real data is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> extremely</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> classified...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; This would be great news for an Orion type<br>
ground launch, except for the EMP.<br>
&gt; Of course the article at NS covers the EMP effect<br>
to some degree.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I objected to the basic premise that EMP is a consideration: Everything we know says that EMP is caused by extremely huge bursts (several MT plus), or maybe very much smaller bursts, which are specially designed to maximize it (directed, enhanced gamma production?).<br>
 Orion thrust bombs are very small, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> not</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> designed to maximize it, or maybe designed to minimize it. It just doesn't seem to be a big consideration.<br>
<br>
 Minimize gammas, to minimize EMP, with maximum possible prompt heat flash relative to all other effects, to provide the most energy to the propellant injected into the explosion.<br>
 We know that fairly clean, small bombs can be made to maximize neutrons. I don't know if that helps an Orion any, but it does indicate that there's a wide variety of possible bomb designs for different effects.<br>
It doesn't bother us if there's an intense prompt flash of radiation. The ship itself is protected, and there's nothing else nearby to be hurt. We obviously don't use stuff like cobalt jackets to maximize lingering radiation! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ustifled.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stifled</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/15/02 12:10:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who knows?</span><hr size=1> In an Orion bomb, you wish to maximise x-rays.<br>
